[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Pitched in Aroer.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The census began on the east of Jordan, at the extreme south, thence passed northwards through the eastern tribes, and crossing the Jordan, passed southwards through the western tribes. Aroer is the city described in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as on the river Arnon, at the extreme southern border of the trans-Jordanie territory.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of Gad.—This follows the Masoretic reading. It is better to put a period after the word river, and for “of Gad” to read “towards Gad.” Perhaps the words “and they came” (towards Gad) may have been lost from the text.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Of Gad.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—This follows the Masoretic reading. It is better to put a period after the word ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "river",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", and for “of Gad” to read “towards Gad.” Perhaps the words “and they came” (towards Gad) may have been lost from the text.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Jazer.—A boundary city of Gad (Joshua 13:25). Thence they went to Gilead.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Jazer.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—A boundary city of Gad (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Joshua 13:25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). Thence they went to Gilead.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:5-7",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 24:5-7",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They passed over Jordan — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "They went first into the eastern part of the country, and so by the northern coasts to the west, and then to the south. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And pitched in Aroer — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "These words seem to import, that they pitched their tents in the field, and thither summoned the neighbouring towns to come unto them: which was very troublesome, and at last proved intolerably grievous. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And to the land of Tahtim-hodshi — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "It is in vain to seek after this land, which is not mentioned in the book of Joshua, but, it is likely, was near to Gilead; and had been lately recovered, some think, from other people, and was now inhabited by the Israelites. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And they came to — about Zidon — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Not to the city of Zidon, for that was not in their power; but to the coast about it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And came to the strong hold of Tyre — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To the territory near it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And to all the cities of the Hivites, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — Who lived in those north-west parts of the country. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Even to Beer-sheba — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "On the south side.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "24:1-9 For the people's sin David was left to act wrong, and in his chastisement they received punishment. This example throws light upon God's government of the world, and furnishes a useful lesson. The pride of David's heart, was his sin in numbering of the people. He thought thereby to appear the more formidable, trusting in an arm of flesh more than he should have done, and though he had written so much of trusting in God only. God judges not of sin as we do. What appears to us harmless, or, at least, but a small offence, may be a great sin in the eye of God, who discerns the thoughts and intents of the heart. Even ungodly men can discern evil tempers and wrong conduct in believers, of which they themselves often remain unconscious. But God seldom allows those whom he loves the pleasures they sinfully covet.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Aroer - Aroer on the Arnon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " note). Aroer itself stood on the very edge of the precipitous cliff of the valley; and in the valley beneath, possibly in an island in the stream, stood another city which is here alluded to.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "River - Rather, \"the valley\" (margin). They passed from Aroer, northward to Gad, and so pitched at Jazer (see the marginal references), which is on the frontier of Gad and Reuben. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "River - Rather, \"the valley\" (margin). They passed from Aroer, northward to Gad, and so pitched at Jazer (see the marginal references), which is on the frontier of Gad and Reuben. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
